#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:4
msgid "Python Types and C-Structures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:8
msgid ""
"Several new types are defined in the C-code. Most of these are accessible "
"from Python, but a few are not exposed due to their limited use. Every new "
"Python type has an associated :c:expr:`PyObject *` with an internal "
"structure that includes a pointer to a \"method table\" that defines how the "
"new object behaves in Python. When you receive a Python object into C code, "
"you always get a pointer to a :c:type:`PyObject` structure. Because a :c:"
"type:`PyObject` structure is very generic and defines only :c:macro:"
"`PyObject_HEAD`, by itself it is not very interesting. However, different "
"objects contain more details after the :c:macro:`PyObject_HEAD` (but you "
"have to cast to the correct type to access them --- or use accessor "
"functions or macros)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:22
msgid "New Python Types Defined"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:24
msgid ""
"Python types are the functional equivalent in C of classes in Python. By "
"constructing a new Python type you make available a new object for Python. "
"The ndarray object is an example of a new type defined in C. New types are "
"defined in C by two basic steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:29
msgid ""
"creating a C-structure (usually named ``Py{Name}Object``) that is binary- "
"compatible with the :c:type:`PyObject` structure itself but holds the "
"additional information needed for that particular object;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:33
msgid ""
"populating the :c:type:`PyTypeObject` table (pointed to by the ob_type "
"member of the :c:type:`PyObject` structure) with pointers to functions that "
"implement the desired behavior for the type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:37
msgid ""
"Instead of special method names which define behavior for Python classes, "
"there are \"function tables\" which point to functions that implement the "
"desired results. Since Python 2.2, the PyTypeObject itself has become "
"dynamic which allows C types that can be \"sub-typed \"from other C-types in "
"C, and sub-classed in Python. The children types inherit the attributes and "
"methods from their parent(s)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:44
msgid ""
"There are two major new types: the ndarray ( :c:data:`PyArray_Type` ) and "
"the ufunc ( :c:data:`PyUFunc_Type` ). Additional types play a supportive "
"role: the :c:data:`PyArrayIter_Type`, the :c:data:`PyArrayMultiIter_Type`, "
"and the :c:data:`PyArrayDescr_Type` . The :c:data:`PyArrayIter_Type` is the "
"type for a flat iterator for an ndarray (the object that is returned when "
"getting the flat attribute). The :c:data:`PyArrayMultiIter_Type` is the type "
"of the object returned when calling ``broadcast`` (). It handles iteration "
"and broadcasting over a collection of nested sequences. Also, the :c:data:"
"`PyArrayDescr_Type` is the data-type-descriptor type whose instances "
"describe the data.  Finally, there are 21 new scalar-array types which are "
"new Python scalars corresponding to each of the fundamental data types "
"available for arrays. An additional 10 other types are place holders that "
"allow the array scalars to fit into a hierarchy of actual Python types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:62
msgid "PyArray_Type and PyArrayObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:66
msgid ""
"The Python type of the ndarray is :c:data:`PyArray_Type`. In C, every "
"ndarray is a pointer to a :c:type:`PyArrayObject` structure. The ob_type "
"member of this structure contains a pointer to the :c:data:`PyArray_Type` "
"typeobject."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:74
msgid ""
"The :c:type:`PyArrayObject` C-structure contains all of the required "
"information for an array. All instances of an ndarray (and its subclasses) "
"will have this structure.  For future compatibility, these structure members "
"should normally be accessed using the provided macros. If you need a shorter "
"name, then you can make use of :c:type:`NPY_AO` (deprecated) which is "
"defined to be equivalent to :c:type:`PyArrayObject`. Direct access to the "
"struct fields are deprecated. Use the ``PyArray_*(arr)`` form instead. As of "
"NumPy 1.20, the size of this struct is not considered part of the NumPy ABI "
"(see note at the end of the member list)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:85
msgid ""
"typedef struct PyArrayObject {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    char *data;\n"
"    int nd;\n"
"    npy_intp *dimensions;\n"
"    npy_intp *strides;\n"
"    PyObject *base;\n"
"    PyArray_Descr *descr;\n"
"    int flags;\n"
"    PyObject *weakreflist;\n"
"    /* version dependent private members */\n"
"} PyArrayObject;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:102
msgid ""
"This is needed by all Python objects. It consists of (at least) a reference "
"count member ( ``ob_refcnt`` ) and a pointer to the typeobject "
"( ``ob_type`` ). (Other elements may also be present if Python was compiled "
"with special options see Include/object.h in the Python source tree for more "
"information). The ob_type member points to a Python type object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:112
msgid ""
"Accessible via :c:data:`PyArray_DATA`, this data member is a pointer to the "
"first element of the array. This pointer can (and normally should) be recast "
"to the data type of the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:118
msgid ""
"An integer providing the number of dimensions for this array. When nd is 0, "
"the array is sometimes called a rank-0 array. Such arrays have undefined "
"dimensions and strides and cannot be accessed. Macro :c:data:`PyArray_NDIM` "
"defined in ``ndarraytypes.h`` points to this data member. :c:data:"
"`NPY_MAXDIMS` is the largest number of dimensions for any array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:127
msgid ""
"An array of integers providing the shape in each dimension as long as nd :"
"math:`\\geq` 1. The integer is always large enough to hold a pointer on the "
"platform, so the dimension size is only limited by memory. :c:data:"
"`PyArray_DIMS` is the macro associated with this data member."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:135
msgid ""
"An array of integers providing for each dimension the number of bytes that "
"must be skipped to get to the next element in that dimension. Associated "
"with macro :c:data:`PyArray_STRIDES`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:141
msgid ""
"Pointed to by :c:data:`PyArray_BASE`, this member is used to hold a pointer "
"to another Python object that is related to this array. There are two use "
"cases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:145
msgid ""
"If this array does not own its own memory, then base points to the Python "
"object that owns it (perhaps another array object)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:147
msgid ""
"If this array has the :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_WRITEBACKIFCOPY` flag set, then "
"this array is a working copy of a \"misbehaved\" array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:150
msgid ""
"When ``PyArray_ResolveWritebackIfCopy`` is called, the array pointed to by "
"base will be updated with the contents of this array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:155
msgid ""
"A pointer to a data-type descriptor object (see below). The data-type "
"descriptor object is an instance of a new built-in type which allows a "
"generic description of memory. There is a descriptor structure for each data "
"type supported. This descriptor structure contains useful information about "
"the type as well as a pointer to a table of function pointers to implement "
"specific functionality. As the name suggests, it is associated with the "
"macro :c:data:`PyArray_DESCR`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:166
msgid ""
"Pointed to by the macro :c:data:`PyArray_FLAGS`, this data member represents "
"the flags indicating how the memory pointed to by data is to be interpreted. "
"Possible flags are :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_C_CONTIGUOUS`, :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_F_CONTIGUOUS`, :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_OWNDATA`, :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_ALIGNED`, :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_WRITEABLE`, :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_WRITEBACKIFCOPY`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:175
msgid ""
"This member allows array objects to have weak references (using the weakref "
"module)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:180
msgid ""
"Further members are considered private and version dependent. If the size of "
"the struct is important for your code, special care must be taken. A "
"possible use-case when this is relevant is subclassing in C. If your code "
"relies on ``sizeof(PyArrayObject)`` to be constant, you must add the "
"following check at import time:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:186
msgid ""
"if (sizeof(PyArrayObject) < PyArray_Type.tp_basicsize) {\n"
"    PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ImportError,\n"
"       \"Binary incompatibility with NumPy, must recompile/update X.\");\n"
"    return NULL;\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:194
msgid ""
"To ensure that your code does not have to be compiled for a specific NumPy "
"version, you may add a constant, leaving room for changes in NumPy. A "
"solution guaranteed to be compatible with any future NumPy version requires "
"the use of a runtime calculate offset and allocation size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:201
msgid "PyArrayDescr_Type and PyArray_Descr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:205
msgid ""
"The :c:data:`PyArrayDescr_Type` is the built-in type of the data-type-"
"descriptor objects used to describe how the bytes comprising the array are "
"to be interpreted.  There are 21 statically-defined :c:type:`PyArray_Descr` "
"objects for the built-in data-types. While these participate in reference "
"counting, their reference count should never reach zero.  There is also a "
"dynamic table of user-defined :c:type:`PyArray_Descr` objects that is also "
"maintained. Once a data-type-descriptor object is \"registered\" it should "
"never be deallocated either. The function :c:func:`PyArray_DescrFromType` "
"(...) can be used to retrieve a :c:type:`PyArray_Descr` object from an "
"enumerated type-number (either built-in or user- defined)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:219
msgid ""
"The :c:type:`PyArray_Descr` structure lies at the heart of the :c:data:"
"`PyArrayDescr_Type`. While it is described here for completeness, it should "
"be considered internal to NumPy and manipulated via ``PyArrayDescr_*`` or "
"``PyDataType*`` functions and macros. The size of this structure is subject "
"to change across versions of NumPy. To ensure compatibility:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:226
#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:792
msgid "Never declare a non-pointer instance of the struct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:227
#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:793
msgid "Never perform pointer arithmetic"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:228
msgid "Never use ``sizeof(PyArray_Descr)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:230
#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:796
msgid "It has the following structure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:232
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    PyTypeObject *typeobj;\n"
"    char kind;\n"
"    char type;\n"
"    char byteorder;\n"
"    char flags;\n"
"    int type_num;\n"
"    int elsize;\n"
"    int alignment;\n"
"    PyArray_ArrayDescr *subarray;\n"
"    PyObject *fields;\n"
"    PyObject *names;\n"
"    PyArray_ArrFuncs *f;\n"
"    PyObject *metadata;\n"
"    NpyAuxData *c_metadata;\n"
"    npy_hash_t hash;\n"
"} PyArray_Descr;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:255
msgid ""
"Pointer to a typeobject that is the corresponding Python type for the "
"elements of this array. For the builtin types, this points to the "
"corresponding array scalar. For user-defined types, this should point to a "
"user-defined typeobject. This typeobject can either inherit from array "
"scalars or not. If it does not inherit from array scalars, then the :c:data:"
"`NPY_USE_GETITEM` and :c:data:`NPY_USE_SETITEM` flags should be set in the "
"``flags`` member."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:265
msgid ""
"A character code indicating the kind of array (using the array interface "
"typestring notation). A 'b' represents Boolean, a 'i' represents signed "
"integer, a 'u' represents unsigned integer, 'f' represents floating point, "
"'c' represents complex floating point, 'S' represents 8-bit zero-terminated "
"bytes, 'U' represents 32-bit/character unicode string, and 'V' represents "
"arbitrary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:274
msgid "A traditional character code indicating the data type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:278
msgid ""
"A character indicating the byte-order: '>' (big-endian), '<' (little- "
"endian), '=' (native), '\\|' (irrelevant, ignore). All builtin data- types "
"have byteorder '='."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:284
msgid ""
"A data-type bit-flag that determines if the data-type exhibits object- array "
"like behavior. Each bit in this member is a flag which are named as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:288
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_ITEM_REFCOUNT`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:289
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_ITEM_HASOBJECT`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:290
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_LIST_PICKLE`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:291
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_ITEM_IS_POINTER`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:292
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_NEEDS_INIT`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:293
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_NEEDS_PYAPI`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:294
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_USE_GETITEM`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:295
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_USE_SETITEM`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:296
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_FROM_FIELDS`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:297
msgid ":c:macro:`NPY_OBJECT_DTYPE_FLAGS`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:301
msgid ""
"A number that uniquely identifies the data type. For new data-types, this "
"number is assigned when the data-type is registered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:306
msgid ""
"For data types that are always the same size (such as long), this holds the "
"size of the data type. For flexible data types where different arrays can "
"have a different elementsize, this should be 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:313
msgid ""
"A number providing alignment information for this data type. Specifically, "
"it shows how far from the start of a 2-element structure (whose first "
"element is a ``char`` ), the compiler places an item of this type: "
"``offsetof(struct {char c; type v;}, v)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:321
msgid ""
"If this is non- ``NULL``, then this data-type descriptor is a C-style "
"contiguous array of another data-type descriptor. In other-words, each "
"element that this descriptor describes is actually an array of some other "
"base descriptor. This is most useful as the data-type descriptor for a field "
"in another data-type descriptor. The fields member should be ``NULL`` if "
"this is non- ``NULL`` (the fields member of the base descriptor can be non- "
"``NULL`` however)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:332
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyArray_Descr *base;\n"
"    PyObject *shape;\n"
"} PyArray_ArrayDescr;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:341
msgid "The data-type-descriptor object of the base-type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:345
msgid ""
"The shape (always C-style contiguous) of the sub-array as a Python tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:350
msgid ""
"If this is non-NULL, then this data-type-descriptor has fields described by "
"a Python dictionary whose keys are names (and also titles if given) and "
"whose values are tuples that describe the fields. Recall that a data-type-"
"descriptor always describes a fixed-length set of bytes. A field is a named "
"sub-region of that total, fixed-length collection. A field is described by a "
"tuple composed of another data- type-descriptor and a byte offset. "
"Optionally, the tuple may contain a title which is normally a Python string. "
"These tuples are placed in this dictionary keyed by name (and also title if "
"given)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:363
msgid "An ordered tuple of field names. It is NULL if no field is defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:368
msgid ""
"A pointer to a structure containing functions that the type needs to "
"implement internal features. These functions are not the same thing as the "
"universal functions (ufuncs) described later. Their signatures can vary "
"arbitrarily."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:375
msgid "Metadata about this dtype."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:379
msgid ""
"Metadata specific to the C implementation of the particular dtype. Added for "
"NumPy 1.7.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:385
msgid "Currently unused. Reserved for future use in caching hash values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:390
msgid ""
"Indicates that items of this data-type must be reference counted (using :c:"
"func:`Py_INCREF` and :c:func:`Py_DECREF` )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:395
msgid "Same as :c:data:`NPY_ITEM_REFCOUNT`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:399
msgid ""
"Indicates arrays of this data-type must be converted to a list before "
"pickling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:404
msgid "Indicates the item is a pointer to some other data-type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:408
msgid ""
"Indicates memory for this data-type must be initialized (set to 0) on "
"creation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:413
msgid ""
"Indicates this data-type requires the Python C-API during access (so don't "
"give up the GIL if array access is going to be needed)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:419
msgid ""
"On array access use the ``f->getitem`` function pointer instead of the "
"standard conversion to an array scalar. Must use if you don't define an "
"array scalar to go along with the data-type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:426
msgid ""
"When creating a 0-d array from an array scalar use ``f->setitem`` instead of "
"the standard copy from an array scalar. Must use if you don't define an "
"array scalar to go along with the data-type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:433
msgid ""
"The bits that are inherited for the parent data-type if these bits are set "
"in any field of the data-type. Currently ( :c:data:`NPY_NEEDS_INIT` \\| :c:"
"data:`NPY_LIST_PICKLE` \\| :c:data:`NPY_ITEM_REFCOUNT` \\| :c:data:"
"`NPY_NEEDS_PYAPI` )."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:440
msgid ""
"Bits set for the object data-type: ( :c:data:`NPY_LIST_PICKLE` \\| :c:data:"
"`NPY_USE_GETITEM` \\| :c:data:`NPY_ITEM_IS_POINTER` \\| :c:data:"
"`NPY_ITEM_REFCOUNT` \\| :c:data:`NPY_NEEDS_INIT` \\| :c:data:"
"`NPY_NEEDS_PYAPI`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:447
msgid "Return true if all the given flags are set for the data-type object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:452
msgid ""
"Equivalent to :c:func:`PyDataType_FLAGCHK` (*dtype*, :c:data:"
"`NPY_ITEM_REFCOUNT`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:457
msgid ""
"Functions implementing internal features. Not all of these function pointers "
"must be defined for a given type. The required members are ``nonzero``, "
"``copyswap``, ``copyswapn``, ``setitem``, ``getitem``, and ``cast``. These "
"are assumed to be non- ``NULL`` and ``NULL`` entries will cause a program "
"crash. The other functions may be ``NULL`` which will just mean reduced "
"functionality for that data-type. (Also, the nonzero function will be filled "
"in with a default function if it is ``NULL`` when you register a user-"
"defined data-type)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:467
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyArray_VectorUnaryFunc *cast[NPY_NTYPES];\n"
"    PyArray_GetItemFunc *getitem;\n"
"    PyArray_SetItemFunc *setitem;\n"
"    PyArray_CopySwapNFunc *copyswapn;\n"
"    PyArray_CopySwapFunc *copyswap;\n"
"    PyArray_CompareFunc *compare;\n"
"    PyArray_ArgFunc *argmax;\n"
"    PyArray_DotFunc *dotfunc;\n"
"    PyArray_ScanFunc *scanfunc;\n"
"    PyArray_FromStrFunc *fromstr;\n"
"    PyArray_NonzeroFunc *nonzero;\n"
"    PyArray_FillFunc *fill;\n"
"    PyArray_FillWithScalarFunc *fillwithscalar;\n"
"    PyArray_SortFunc *sort[NPY_NSORTS];\n"
"    PyArray_ArgSortFunc *argsort[NPY_NSORTS];\n"
"    PyObject *castdict;\n"
"    PyArray_ScalarKindFunc *scalarkind;\n"
"    int **cancastscalarkindto;\n"
"    int *cancastto;\n"
"    PyArray_FastClipFunc *fastclip;  /* deprecated */\n"
"    PyArray_FastPutmaskFunc *fastputmask;  /* deprecated */\n"
"    PyArray_FastTakeFunc *fasttake;  /* deprecated */\n"
"    PyArray_ArgFunc *argmin;\n"
"} PyArray_ArrFuncs;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:495
msgid ""
"The concept of a behaved segment is used in the description of the function "
"pointers. A behaved segment is one that is aligned and in native machine "
"byte-order for the data-type. The ``nonzero``, ``copyswap``, ``copyswapn``, "
"``getitem``, and ``setitem`` functions can (and must) deal with mis-behaved "
"arrays. The other functions require behaved memory segments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:505
msgid ""
"An array of function pointers to cast from the current type to all of the "
"other builtin types. Each function casts a contiguous, aligned, and "
"notswapped buffer pointed at by *from* to a contiguous, aligned, and "
"notswapped buffer pointed at by *to* The number of items to cast is given by "
"*n*, and the arguments *fromarr* and *toarr* are interpreted as "
"PyArrayObjects for flexible arrays to get itemsize information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:516
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that returns a standard Python object from a single "
"element of the array object *arr* pointed to by *data*. This function must "
"be able to deal with \"misbehaved \"(misaligned and/or swapped) arrays "
"correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:523
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that sets the Python object *item* into the array, "
"*arr*, at the position pointed to by *data* . This function deals with "
"\"misbehaved\" arrays. If successful, a zero is returned, otherwise, a "
"negative one is returned (and a Python error set)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:535
msgid ""
"These members are both pointers to functions to copy data from *src* to "
"*dest* and *swap* if indicated. The value of arr is only used for flexible "
"( :c:data:`NPY_STRING`, :c:data:`NPY_UNICODE`, and :c:data:`NPY_VOID` ) "
"arrays (and is obtained from ``arr->descr->elsize`` ). The second function "
"copies a single value, while the first loops over n values with the provided "
"strides. These functions can deal with misbehaved *src* data. If *src* is "
"NULL then no copy is performed. If *swap* is 0, then no byteswapping occurs. "
"It is assumed that *dest* and *src* do not overlap. If they overlap, then "
"use ``memmove`` (...) first followed by ``copyswap(n)`` with NULL valued "
"``src``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:550
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that compares two elements of the array, ``arr``, "
"pointed to by ``d1`` and ``d2``. This function requires behaved (aligned and "
"not swapped) arrays. The return value is 1 if * ``d1`` > * ``d2``, 0 if * "
"``d1`` == * ``d2``, and -1 if * ``d1`` < * ``d2``. The array object ``arr`` "
"is used to retrieve itemsize and field information for flexible arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:560
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that retrieves the index of the largest of ``n`` "
"elements in ``arr`` beginning at the element pointed to by ``data``. This "
"function requires that the memory segment be contiguous and behaved. The "
"return value is always 0. The index of the largest element is returned in "
"``max_ind``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:571
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that multiplies two ``n`` -length sequences "
"together, adds them, and places the result in element pointed to by ``op`` "
"of ``arr``. The start of the two sequences are pointed to by ``ip1`` and "
"``ip2``. To get to the next element in each sequence requires a jump of "
"``is1`` and ``is2`` *bytes*, respectively. This function requires behaved "
"(though not necessarily contiguous) memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:581
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that scans (scanf style) one element of the "
"corresponding type from the file descriptor ``fd`` into the array memory "
"pointed to by ``ip``. The array is assumed to be behaved. The last argument "
"``arr`` is the array to be scanned into. Returns number of receiving "
"arguments successfully assigned (which may be zero in case a matching "
"failure occurred before the first receiving argument was assigned), or EOF "
"if input failure occurs before the first receiving argument was assigned. "
"This function should be called without holding the Python GIL, and has to "
"grab it for error reporting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:595
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that converts the string pointed to by ``str`` to "
"one element of the corresponding type and places it in the memory location "
"pointed to by ``ip``. After the conversion is completed, ``*endptr`` points "
"to the rest of the string. The last argument ``arr`` is the array into which "
"ip points (needed for variable-size data- types). Returns 0 on success or -1 "
"on failure. Requires a behaved array. This function should be called without "
"holding the Python GIL, and has to grab it for error reporting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:607
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that returns TRUE if the item of ``arr`` pointed to "
"by ``data`` is nonzero. This function can deal with misbehaved arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:613
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that fills a contiguous array of given length with "
"data. The first two elements of the array must already be filled- in. From "
"these two values, a delta will be computed and the values from item 3 to the "
"end will be computed by repeatedly adding this computed delta. The data "
"buffer must be well-behaved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:623
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that fills a contiguous ``buffer`` of the given "
"``length`` with a single scalar ``value`` whose address is given. The final "
"argument is the array which is needed to get the itemsize for variable-"
"length arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:630
msgid ""
"An array of function pointers to a particular sorting algorithms. A "
"particular sorting algorithm is obtained using a key (so far :c:data:"
"`NPY_QUICKSORT`, :c:data:`NPY_HEAPSORT`, and :c:data:`NPY_MERGESORT` are "
"defined). These sorts are done in-place assuming contiguous and aligned data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:639
msgid ""
"An array of function pointers to sorting algorithms for this data type. The "
"same sorting algorithms as for sort are available. The indices producing the "
"sort are returned in ``result`` (which must be initialized with indices 0 to "
"``length-1`` inclusive)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:647
msgid ""
"Either ``NULL`` or a dictionary containing low-level casting functions for "
"user- defined data-types. Each function is wrapped in a :c:expr:`PyCapsule "
"*` and keyed by the data-type number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:654
msgid ""
"A function to determine how scalars of this type should be interpreted. The "
"argument is ``NULL`` or a 0-dimensional array containing the data (if that "
"is needed to determine the kind of scalar). The return value must be of "
"type :c:type:`NPY_SCALARKIND`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:662
msgid ""
"Either ``NULL`` or an array of :c:type:`NPY_NSCALARKINDS` pointers. These "
"pointers should each be either ``NULL`` or a pointer to an array of integers "
"(terminated by :c:data:`NPY_NOTYPE`) indicating data-types that a scalar of "
"this data-type of the specified kind can be cast to safely (this usually "
"means without losing precision)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:671
msgid ""
"Either ``NULL`` or an array of integers (terminated by :c:data:"
"`NPY_NOTYPE` ) indicated data-types that this data-type can be cast to "
"safely (this usually means without losing precision)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:679
msgid ""
"The use of this function will give a deprecation warning when ``np.clip``. "
"Instead of this function, the datatype must instead use "
"``PyUFunc_RegisterLoopForDescr`` to attach a custom loop to ``np.core.umath."
"clip``, ``np.minimum``, and ``np.maximum``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:685
#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:698
#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:714
msgid ""
"Setting this function is deprecated and should always be ``NULL``, if set, "
"it will be ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:689
msgid ""
"A function that reads ``n_in`` items from ``in``, and writes to ``out`` the "
"read value if it is within the limits pointed to by ``min`` and ``max``, or "
"the corresponding limit if outside. The memory segments must be contiguous "
"and behaved, and either ``min`` or ``max`` may be ``NULL``, but not both."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:702
msgid ""
"A function that takes a pointer ``in`` to an array of ``n_in`` items, a "
"pointer ``mask`` to an array of ``n_in`` boolean values, and a pointer "
"``vals`` to an array of ``nv`` items. Items from ``vals`` are copied into "
"``in`` wherever the value in ``mask`` is non-zero, tiling ``vals`` as needed "
"if ``nv < n_in``. All arrays must be contiguous and behaved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:718
msgid ""
"A function that takes a pointer ``src`` to a C contiguous, behaved segment, "
"interpreted as a 3-dimensional array of shape ``(n_outer, nindarray, "
"nelem)``, a pointer ``indarray`` to a contiguous, behaved segment of "
"``m_middle`` integer indices, and a pointer ``dest`` to a C contiguous, "
"behaved segment, interpreted as a 3-dimensional array of shape ``(n_outer, "
"m_middle, nelem)``. The indices in ``indarray`` are used to index ``src`` "
"along the second dimension, and copy the corresponding chunks of ``nelem`` "
"items into ``dest``. ``clipmode`` (which can take on the values :c:data:"
"`NPY_RAISE`, :c:data:`NPY_WRAP` or :c:data:`NPY_CLIP`) determines how will "
"indices smaller than 0 or larger than ``nindarray`` will be handled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:735
msgid ""
"A pointer to a function that retrieves the index of the smallest of ``n`` "
"elements in ``arr`` beginning at the element pointed to by ``data``. This "
"function requires that the memory segment be contiguous and behaved. The "
"return value is always 0. The index of the smallest element is returned in "
"``min_ind``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:743
msgid ""
"The :c:data:`PyArray_Type` typeobject implements many of the features of :c:"
"type:`Python objects <PyTypeObject>` including the :c:member:`tp_as_number "
"<PyTypeObject.tp_as_number>`, :c:member:`tp_as_sequence <PyTypeObject."
"tp_as_sequence>`, :c:member:`tp_as_mapping <PyTypeObject.tp_as_mapping>`, "
"and :c:member:`tp_as_buffer <PyTypeObject.tp_as_buffer>` interfaces. The :c:"
"type:`rich comparison <richcmpfunc>`) is also used along with new-style "
"attribute lookup for member (:c:member:`tp_members <PyTypeObject."
"tp_members>`) and properties (:c:member:`tp_getset <PyTypeObject."
"tp_getset>`). The :c:data:`PyArray_Type` can also be sub-typed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:756
msgid ""
"The ``tp_as_number`` methods use a generic approach to call whatever "
"function has been registered for handling the operation.  When the "
"``_multiarray_umath module`` is imported, it sets the numeric operations for "
"all arrays to the corresponding ufuncs. This choice can be changed with :c:"
"func:`PyUFunc_ReplaceLoopBySignature` The ``tp_str`` and ``tp_repr`` methods "
"can also be altered using :c:func:`PyArray_SetStringFunction`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:765
msgid "PyUFunc_Type and PyUFuncObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:769
msgid ""
"The ufunc object is implemented by creation of the :c:data:`PyUFunc_Type`. "
"It is a very simple type that implements only basic getattribute behavior, "
"printing behavior, and has call behavior which allows these objects to act "
"like functions. The basic idea behind the ufunc is to hold a reference to "
"fast 1-dimensional (vector) loops for each data type that supports the "
"operation. These one-dimensional loops all have the same signature and are "
"the key to creating a new ufunc. They are called by the generic looping code "
"as appropriate to implement the N-dimensional function. There are also some "
"generic 1-d loops defined for floating and complexfloating arrays that allow "
"you to define a ufunc using a single scalar function (*e.g.* atanh)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:785
msgid ""
"The core of the ufunc is the :c:type:`PyUFuncObject` which contains all the "
"information needed to call the underlying C-code loops that perform the "
"actual work. While it is described here for completeness, it should be "
"considered internal to NumPy and manipulated via ``PyUFunc_*`` functions. "
"The size of this structure is subject to change across versions of NumPy. To "
"ensure compatibility:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:794
msgid "Never use ``sizeof(PyUFuncObject)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:798
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    int nin;\n"
"    int nout;\n"
"    int nargs;\n"
"    int identity;\n"
"    PyUFuncGenericFunction *functions;\n"
"    void **data;\n"
"    int ntypes;\n"
"    int reserved1;\n"
"    const char *name;\n"
"    char *types;\n"
"    const char *doc;\n"
"    void *ptr;\n"
"    PyObject *obj;\n"
"    PyObject *userloops;\n"
"    int core_enabled;\n"
"    int core_num_dim_ix;\n"
"    int *core_num_dims;\n"
"    int *core_dim_ixs;\n"
"    int *core_offsets;\n"
"    char *core_signature;\n"
"    PyUFunc_TypeResolutionFunc *type_resolver;\n"
"    PyUFunc_LegacyInnerLoopSelectionFunc *legacy_inner_loop_selector;\n"
"    void *reserved2;\n"
"    npy_uint32 *op_flags;\n"
"    npy_uint32 *iter_flags;\n"
"    /* new in API version 0x0000000D */\n"
"    npy_intp *core_dim_sizes;\n"
"    npy_uint32 *core_dim_flags;\n"
"    PyObject *identity_value;\n"
"    /* Further private slots (size depends on the NumPy version) */\n"
"} PyUFuncObject;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:840
msgid "The number of input arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:844
msgid "The number of output arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:848
msgid ""
"The total number of arguments (*nin* + *nout*). This must be less than :c:"
"data:`NPY_MAXARGS`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:853
msgid ""
"Either :c:data:`PyUFunc_One`, :c:data:`PyUFunc_Zero`, :c:data:"
"`PyUFunc_MinusOne`, :c:data:`PyUFunc_None`, :c:data:"
"`PyUFunc_ReorderableNone`, or :c:data:`PyUFunc_IdentityValue` to indicate "
"the identity for this operation. It is only used for a reduce-like call on "
"an empty array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:863
msgid ""
"An array of function pointers --- one for each data type supported by the "
"ufunc. This is the vector loop that is called to implement the underlying "
"function *dims* [0] times. The first argument, *args*, is an array of "
"*nargs* pointers to behaved memory. Pointers to the data for the input "
"arguments are first, followed by the pointers to the data for the output "
"arguments. How many bytes must be skipped to get to the next element in the "
"sequence is specified by the corresponding entry in the *steps* array. The "
"last argument allows the loop to receive extra information.  This is "
"commonly used so that a single, generic vector loop can be used for multiple "
"functions. In this case, the actual scalar function to call is passed in as "
"*extradata*. The size of this function pointer array is ntypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:880
msgid ""
"Extra data to be passed to the 1-d vector loops or ``NULL`` if no extra-data "
"is needed. This C-array must be the same size ( *i.e.* ntypes) as the "
"functions array. ``NULL`` is used if extra_data is not needed. Several C-API "
"calls for UFuncs are just 1-d vector loops that make use of this extra data "
"to receive a pointer to the actual function to call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:889
msgid ""
"The number of supported data types for the ufunc. This number specifies how "
"many different 1-d loops (of the builtin data types) are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:895
msgid "Unused."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:899
msgid ""
"A string name for the ufunc. This is used dynamically to build the __doc\\__ "
"attribute of ufuncs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:904
msgid ""
"An array of :math:`nargs \\times ntypes` 8-bit type_numbers which contains "
"the type signature for the function for each of the supported (builtin) data "
"types. For each of the *ntypes* functions, the corresponding set of type "
"numbers in this array shows how the *args* argument should be interpreted in "
"the 1-d vector loop. These type numbers do not have to be the same type and "
"mixed-type ufuncs are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:914
msgid ""
"Documentation for the ufunc. Should not contain the function signature as "
"this is generated dynamically when __doc\\__ is retrieved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:920
msgid ""
"Any dynamically allocated memory. Currently, this is used for dynamic ufuncs "
"created from a python function to store room for the types, data, and name "
"members."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:926
msgid ""
"For ufuncs dynamically created from python functions, this member holds a "
"reference to the underlying Python function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:931
msgid ""
"A dictionary of user-defined 1-d vector loops (stored as CObject ptrs) for "
"user-defined types. A loop may be registered by the user for any user-"
"defined type. It is retrieved by type number. User defined type numbers are "
"always larger than :c:data:`NPY_USERDEF`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:939
msgid "0 for scalar ufuncs; 1 for generalized ufuncs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:943
msgid "Number of distinct core dimension names in the signature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:947
msgid "Number of core dimensions of each argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:951
msgid ""
"Dimension indices in a flattened form; indices of argument ``k`` are stored "
"in ``core_dim_ixs[core_offsets[k] : core_offsets[k] + core_numdims[k]]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:957
msgid ""
"Position of 1st core dimension of each argument in ``core_dim_ixs``, "
"equivalent to cumsum(``core_num_dims``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:962
msgid "Core signature string"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:966
msgid ""
"A function which resolves the types and fills an array with the dtypes for "
"the inputs and outputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:973
msgid ""
"Some fallback support for this slot exists, but will be removed eventually.  "
"A universal function that relied on this will have to be ported eventually. "
"See :ref:`NEP 41 <NEP41>` and :ref:`NEP 43 <NEP43>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:980
msgid "For a possible future loop selector with a different signature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:984
msgid "Override the default operand flags for each ufunc operand."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:988
msgid "Override the default nditer flags for the ufunc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:990
msgid "Added in API version 0x0000000D"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:994
msgid ""
"For each distinct core dimension, the possible :ref:`frozen <frozen>` size "
"if :c:data:`UFUNC_CORE_DIM_SIZE_INFERRED` is ``0``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1000
msgid ""
"For each distinct core dimension, a set of flags ( :c:macro:"
"`UFUNC_CORE_DIM_CAN_IGNORE` and :c:macro:`UFUNC_CORE_DIM_SIZE_INFERRED`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1006
msgid ""
"Identity for reduction, when :c:member:`PyUFuncObject.identity` is equal to :"
"c:data:`PyUFunc_IdentityValue`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1011
msgid "if the dim name ends in ``?``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1015
msgid ""
"if the dim size will be determined from the operands and not from a :ref:"
"`frozen <frozen>` signature"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1019
msgid "PyArrayIter_Type and PyArrayIterObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1023
msgid ""
"This is an iterator object that makes it easy to loop over an N-dimensional "
"array. It is the object returned from the flat attribute of an ndarray. It "
"is also used extensively throughout the implementation internals to loop "
"over an N-dimensional array. The tp_as_mapping interface is implemented so "
"that the iterator object can be indexed (using 1-d indexing), and a few "
"methods are implemented through the tp_methods table. This object implements "
"the next method and can be used anywhere an iterator can be used in Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1035
msgid ""
"The C-structure corresponding to an object of :c:data:`PyArrayIter_Type` is "
"the :c:type:`PyArrayIterObject`. The :c:type:`PyArrayIterObject` is used to "
"keep track of a pointer into an N-dimensional array. It contains associated "
"information used to quickly march through the array. The pointer can be "
"adjusted in three basic ways: 1) advance to the \"next\" position in the "
"array in a C-style contiguous fashion, 2) advance to an arbitrary N-"
"dimensional coordinate in the array, and 3) advance to an arbitrary one-"
"dimensional index into the array. The members of the :c:type:"
"`PyArrayIterObject` structure are used in these calculations. Iterator "
"objects keep their own dimension and strides information about an array. "
"This can be adjusted as needed for \"broadcasting,\" or to loop over only "
"specific dimensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1048
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    int   nd_m1;\n"
"    npy_intp  index;\n"
"    npy_intp  size;\n"
"    npy_intp  coordinates[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp  dims_m1[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp  strides[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp  backstrides[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp  factors[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    PyArrayObject *ao;\n"
"    char  *dataptr;\n"
"    npy_bool  contiguous;\n"
"} PyArrayIterObject;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1067
msgid ""
":math:`N-1` where :math:`N` is the number of dimensions in the underlying "
"array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1072
msgid "The current 1-d index into the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1076
msgid "The total size of the underlying array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1080
msgid "An :math:`N` -dimensional index into the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1084
msgid "The size of the array minus 1 in each dimension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1088
msgid ""
"The strides of the array. How many bytes needed to jump to the next element "
"in each dimension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1093
msgid ""
"How many bytes needed to jump from the end of a dimension back to its "
"beginning. Note that ``backstrides[k] == strides[k] * dims_m1[k]``, but it "
"is stored here as an optimization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1099
msgid ""
"This array is used in computing an N-d index from a 1-d index. It contains "
"needed products of the dimensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1104
msgid ""
"A pointer to the underlying ndarray this iterator was created to represent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1109
msgid "This member points to an element in the ndarray indicated by the index."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1114
msgid ""
"This flag is true if the underlying array is :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_C_CONTIGUOUS`. It is used to simplify calculations when possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1119
msgid ""
"How to use an array iterator on a C-level is explained more fully in later "
"sections. Typically, you do not need to concern yourself with the internal "
"structure of the iterator object, and merely interact with it through the "
"use of the macros :c:func:`PyArray_ITER_NEXT` (it), :c:func:"
"`PyArray_ITER_GOTO` (it, dest), or :c:func:`PyArray_ITER_GOTO1D` (it, "
"index). All of these macros require the argument *it* to be a :c:expr:"
"`PyArrayIterObject *`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1129
msgid "PyArrayMultiIter_Type and PyArrayMultiIterObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1133
msgid ""
"This type provides an iterator that encapsulates the concept of "
"broadcasting. It allows :math:`N` arrays to be broadcast together so that "
"the loop progresses in C-style contiguous fashion over the broadcasted "
"array. The corresponding C-structure is the :c:type:`PyArrayMultiIterObject` "
"whose memory layout must begin any object, *obj*, passed in to the :c:func:"
"`PyArray_Broadcast` (obj) function. Broadcasting is performed by adjusting "
"array iterators so that each iterator represents the broadcasted shape and "
"size, but has its strides adjusted so that the correct element from the "
"array is used at each iteration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1147
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    int numiter;\n"
"    npy_intp size;\n"
"    npy_intp index;\n"
"    int nd;\n"
"    npy_intp dimensions[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    PyArrayIterObject *iters[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"} PyArrayMultiIterObject;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1166
msgid "The number of arrays that need to be broadcast to the same shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1170
msgid "The total broadcasted size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1174
msgid "The current (1-d) index into the broadcasted result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1178
msgid "The number of dimensions in the broadcasted result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1182
msgid "The shape of the broadcasted result (only ``nd`` slots are used)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1186
msgid ""
"An array of iterator objects that holds the iterators for the arrays to be "
"broadcast together. On return, the iterators are adjusted for broadcasting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1191
msgid "PyArrayNeighborhoodIter_Type and PyArrayNeighborhoodIterObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1195
msgid ""
"This is an iterator object that makes it easy to loop over an N-dimensional "
"neighborhood."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1200
msgid ""
"The C-structure corresponding to an object of :c:data:"
"`PyArrayNeighborhoodIter_Type` is the :c:type:"
"`PyArrayNeighborhoodIterObject`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1204
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    int nd_m1;\n"
"    npy_intp index, size;\n"
"    npy_intp coordinates[NPY_MAXDIMS]\n"
"    npy_intp dims_m1[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp strides[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp backstrides[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_intp factors[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    PyArrayObject *ao;\n"
"    char *dataptr;\n"
"    npy_bool contiguous;\n"
"    npy_intp bounds[NPY_MAXDIMS][2];\n"
"    npy_intp limits[NPY_MAXDIMS][2];\n"
"    npy_intp limits_sizes[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    npy_iter_get_dataptr_t translate;\n"
"    npy_intp nd;\n"
"    npy_intp dimensions[NPY_MAXDIMS];\n"
"    PyArrayIterObject* _internal_iter;\n"
"    char* constant;\n"
"    int mode;\n"
"} PyArrayNeighborhoodIterObject;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1230
msgid "PyArrayFlags_Type and PyArrayFlagsObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1234
msgid ""
"When the flags attribute is retrieved from Python, a special builtin object "
"of this type is constructed. This special type makes it easier to work with "
"the different flags by accessing them as attributes or by accessing them as "
"if the object were a dictionary with the flag names as entries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1242
msgid ""
"typedef struct PyArrayFlagsObject {\n"
"        PyObject_HEAD\n"
"        PyObject *arr;\n"
"        int flags;\n"
"} PyArrayFlagsObject;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1252
msgid "ScalarArrayTypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1254
msgid ""
"There is a Python type for each of the different built-in data types that "
"can be present in the array. Most of these are simple wrappers around the "
"corresponding data type in C. The C-names for these types are ``Py{TYPE}"
"ArrType_Type`` where ``{TYPE}`` can be"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1259
msgid ""
"**Bool**, **Byte**, **Short**, **Int**, **Long**, **LongLong**, **UByte**, "
"**UShort**, **UInt**, **ULong**, **ULongLong**, **Half**, **Float**, "
"**Double**, **LongDouble**, **CFloat**, **CDouble**, **CLongDouble**, "
"**String**, **Unicode**, **Void**, and **Object**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1265
msgid ""
"These type names are part of the C-API and can therefore be created in "
"extension C-code. There is also a ``PyIntpArrType_Type`` and a "
"``PyUIntpArrType_Type`` that are simple substitutes for one of the integer "
"types that can hold a pointer on the platform. The structure of these scalar "
"objects is not exposed to C-code. The function :c:func:"
"`PyArray_ScalarAsCtype` (..) can be used to extract the C-type value from "
"the array scalar and the function :c:func:`PyArray_Scalar` (...) can be used "
"to construct an array scalar from a C-value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1276
msgid "Other C-Structures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1278
msgid ""
"A few new C-structures were found to be useful in the development of NumPy. "
"These C-structures are used in at least one C-API call and are therefore "
"documented here. The main reason these structures were defined is to make it "
"easy to use the Python ParseTuple C-API to convert from Python objects to a "
"useful C-Object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1286
msgid "PyArray_Dims"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1290
msgid ""
"This structure is very useful when shape and/or strides information is "
"supposed to be interpreted. The structure is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1293
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    npy_intp *ptr;\n"
"    int len;\n"
"} PyArray_Dims;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1300
msgid "The members of this structure are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1304
msgid ""
"A pointer to a list of (:c:type:`npy_intp`) integers which usually represent "
"array shape or array strides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1309
msgid ""
"The length of the list of integers. It is assumed safe to access *ptr* [0] "
"to *ptr* [len-1]."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1314
msgid "PyArray_Chunk"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1318
msgid ""
"This is equivalent to the buffer object structure in Python up to the ptr "
"member. On 32-bit platforms (*i.e.* if :c:data:`NPY_SIZEOF_INT` == :c:data:"
"`NPY_SIZEOF_INTP`), the len member also matches an equivalent member of the "
"buffer object. It is useful to represent a generic single-segment chunk of "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1324
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    PyObject_HEAD\n"
"    PyObject *base;\n"
"    void *ptr;\n"
"    npy_intp len;\n"
"    int flags;\n"
"} PyArray_Chunk;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1334
msgid "The members are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1344
msgid ""
"The Python object this chunk of memory comes from. Needed so that memory can "
"be accounted for properly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1349
msgid "A pointer to the start of the single-segment chunk of memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1353
msgid "The length of the segment in bytes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1357
msgid ""
"Any data flags (*e.g.* :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_WRITEABLE` ) that should be used "
"to interpret the memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1362
msgid "PyArrayInterface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1364
msgid ":ref:`arrays.interface`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1368
msgid ""
"The :c:type:`PyArrayInterface` structure is defined so that NumPy and other "
"extension modules can use the rapid array interface protocol. The :obj:"
"`~object.__array_struct__` method of an object that supports the rapid array "
"interface protocol should return a :c:type:`PyCapsule` that contains a "
"pointer to a :c:type:`PyArrayInterface` structure with the relevant details "
"of the array. After the new array is created, the attribute should be "
"``DECREF``'d which will free the :c:type:`PyArrayInterface` structure. "
"Remember to ``INCREF`` the object (whose :obj:`~object.__array_struct__` "
"attribute was retrieved) and point the base member of the new :c:type:"
"`PyArrayObject` to this same object. In this way the memory for the array "
"will be managed correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1381
msgid ""
"typedef struct {\n"
"    int two;\n"
"    int nd;\n"
"    char typekind;\n"
"    int itemsize;\n"
"    int flags;\n"
"    npy_intp *shape;\n"
"    npy_intp *strides;\n"
"    void *data;\n"
"    PyObject *descr;\n"
"} PyArrayInterface;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1397
msgid "the integer 2 as a sanity check."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1401
msgid "the number of dimensions in the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1405
msgid ""
"A character indicating what kind of array is present according to the "
"typestring convention with 't' -> bitfield, 'b' -> Boolean, 'i' -> signed "
"integer, 'u' -> unsigned integer, 'f' -> floating point, 'c' -> complex "
"floating point, 'O' -> object, 'S' -> (byte-)string, 'U' -> unicode, 'V' -> "
"void."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1413
msgid "The number of bytes each item in the array requires."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1417
msgid ""
"Any of the bits :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_C_CONTIGUOUS` (1), :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_F_CONTIGUOUS` (2), :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_ALIGNED` (0x100), :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_NOTSWAPPED` (0x200), or :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_WRITEABLE` (0x400) to "
"indicate something about the data. The :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_ALIGNED`, :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARRAY_C_CONTIGUOUS`, and :c:data:`NPY_ARRAY_F_CONTIGUOUS` flags can "
"actually be determined from the other parameters. The flag :c:data:"
"`NPY_ARR_HAS_DESCR` (0x800) can also be set to indicate to objects consuming "
"the version 3 array interface that the descr member of the structure is "
"present (it will be ignored by objects consuming version 2 of the array "
"interface)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1431
msgid "An array containing the size of the array in each dimension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1435
msgid ""
"An array containing the number of bytes to jump to get to the next element "
"in each dimension."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1440
msgid "A pointer *to* the first element of the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1444
msgid ""
"A Python object describing the data-type in more detail (same as the *descr* "
"key in :obj:`~object.__array_interface__`). This can be ``NULL`` if "
"*typekind* and *itemsize* provide enough information. This field is also "
"ignored unless :c:data:`NPY_ARR_HAS_DESCR` flag is on in *flags*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1452
msgid "Internally used structures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1454
msgid ""
"Internally, the code uses some additional Python objects primarily for "
"memory management. These types are not accessible directly from Python, and "
"are not exposed to the C-API. They are included here only for completeness "
"and assistance in understanding the code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1461
msgid ""
"A simple linked-list of C-structures containing the information needed to "
"define a 1-d loop for a ufunc for every defined signature of a user-defined "
"data-type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1467
msgid ""
"Advanced indexing is handled with this Python type. It is simply a loose "
"wrapper around the C-structure containing the variables needed for advanced "
"array indexing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/c-api/types-and-structures.rst:1473
msgid ""
"The C-structure associated with :c:var:`PyArrayMapIter_Type`. This structure "
"is useful if you are trying to understand the advanced-index mapping code. "
"It is defined in the ``arrayobject.h`` header. This type is not exposed to "
"Python and could be replaced with a C-structure. As a Python type it takes "
"advantage of reference- counted memory management."
msgstr ""
